@NODE "mail_84" " Re: Path of libraries "
From: David McMinn <dave@...>
Date: 09-09-02 17:02:51
Subject: @{b}Re: Path of libraries@{ub}

On 9 Sep 2002 at 17:06, Thilo Köhler wrote:

> The reasons why I dont wanted to use libraries:
> (some of them now I know better)
> 
> - libraries stay in memory after usage (?)

Yes, they can do that. However, if you write the CloseLibrary function to call 
your expunge function when the library opencount is 0, your library will remove 
itself.

> - libraries have to be in a special path (?)

No - I think you should be able to put them in any path, but you just need to 
write the full path in the OpenLibrary_() call from your application. In fact, the 
exec.library/OpenLibrary autodoc specifically mentions you can do that :)

> - libraries have a bit more code than the plain instructions

Yes.

> - libraries can have only one instance
> (which make them a bit more complicated to program
> if you need several instances)

Yes.

> - libraries need the ending .library (?)

No, but you need to make sure the name string which is embedded in the library 
file is the same as the filename.

> - libraries are a bit more difficult (wasnt easy to do this in blitz)

Yes - but at least you can write some in basic code rather than 100% assembly 
language. Also, if you ever did open this up to external developers, or change 
language or whatever, the plugins (I guess that's what they are?) would be in a 
standard format that is easier to work with.

> - libraries are visible to the system

Yes - but only if you provide an .FD file or some autodocs or something. If you do 
not do that, people would need to disassemble your library to figure out what it 
does ;)

