There is another way, which also works under AB2 (this allows you to treat the pointer as 
a pointer to an array of any size):

NEWTYPE.fptr
  f.f[0]
End NEWTYPE
*buf.fptr = AllocMem(...)
*buf\f[0] = r

; same as
Poke.f *buf,r

This got around 12.3 million loops / second. If I changed the code with the Poke/Peek to 
access a different item in memory each time ("PokeF(buf+4, r)") then it also got 12.3 
million loops / second.

If I change the code so that it uses a newtype which is just a pointer to a single float 
(and therefore not using an array any more - "*buf\f = r") the PB code gets 15.0 million 
loops / second.

So it does seem that Poke/Peek are slower for simple pokes and peeks which always come 
from the same memory address, but they are the same speed when you are treating memory as 
an array.

