@NODE "mail_102" " tip on easy speedup if needed. "
From: Joar Berntsen <joar.berntsen@...>
Date: 09-24-02 16:21:49
Subject: @{b}tip on easy speedup if needed.@{ub}


If you are making realtime, or any other program genre that
needs to maintain speed, then I have Just recently
discovered how to kill slowdowns when processing
multiple If commands. (especially arrays using them)
here is multiple if endif code.:

if A=1
 if B=1
  if C=1
  D=1
  endif
 endif
endif

now, lets say that A nearly always equals 1.
That means program flow will always go into A's if-endif
and always use cpu cycles doing it.

and B is also very frequently 1, so it also eats cycles

but C however nearly ever is 1.

so why should program flow need to use cycles on
things that nearly never needs it?...

we don't want that ofcourse,
so I suggest this alteration:

if C=1
 if A=1
  if B=1
  D=1
  endif
 endif
endif

now, this code will nearly always be skipped
when program flow reaches >if C=1
thus, cpu cycles are saved, and your prog is faster.
 Since B is less probabal to equal 1,
we could also swap B and A in the above example
for even more speed. 

summary:
use those if's with LEAST probability
first in multiple if structures.


I first used this method this on an array
of about 300 quicks,
and the speed increase was substantial!

I am aware that some multiple if-endif
structures needs to be as they were made,
but my tip is aimed towards those structures
that CAN be altered.


probably many of you, and myself, use the
 If (x=1 AND y=1) OR z=1...etc
but that is not a good idea if you need
to maintain speed, because all variables
will be checked and compared (if im correct)
and it could infact be slower than my first ABCD example.


Im glad to (try to) help ya'll for a change. ;)


