@NODE "mail_121" " Re: using workbench bitmap. "
From: David McMinn <dave@...>
Date: 09-19-02 23:31:47
Subject: @{b}Re: using workbench bitmap.@{ub}

> findscreen 0
> bitmap 0,10,10,8
> screensbitmap 0,0
> use bitmap 0

You should not really "steal" the Workbench screens bitmap like this since you do 
not own it, and changing it as you do here may cause problems with the Workbench 
(for example, if it tries to close the screen).

The best thing to do it to draw to a window on the Workbench screen, or use your own 
screen if you need to draw directly to the screen.

For drawing to a window you can use BitMapToWindow (I think), WBlit, the super 
bitmap commands (PositionSuperBitMap, PutSuperBitmap - for drawing parts of a larger 
bitmap to a window) and any OS function which draws to a rastport (since the 
rastport in a window contains all the necessary clipping).

AFAIK all those methods work on AGA and graphics cards.

PS, you will still need to use the FindScreen command to get access to the Workbench 
screen. After that, SMouseX/Y should work. If you are using a Window to draw to the 
screen, it might be easier to use WMouseX/Y (same as SMouseX/Y but relative to the 
window not the screen) and EMouseX/Y (same as WMouseX/Y but gives the mouse position 
at the last event).


